  "sections": {
    "gp_section_612947718851002939": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "220f57763dd78069a8b80f8bd5117570bc6791d280ea3cffb120c6405123dbe6_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg4t8aUY-gP_text": "Your Safety Boots Are the Problem. Not the Job.",
        "ggPaS9yLzGu_text": "5 reasons UK tradespeople are switching and what's actually different"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947718851002939"
    },
    "gp_section_612947719287210555": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "92c4541c190777bc1011765c71b0e5bd34f49ae09fb69ebccd8878d26d2d4acc_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg8cPHYNwVd_text": "<p>S3 is a performance standard. It defines what a boot has to protect against: impact, penetration, water, slip resistance. It says nothing about what materials you have to use to get there.<br><br>For decades, manufacturers chose steel. Toecap, midsole, reinforcements throughout. It was cheap, it worked, and nobody in the supply chain had a reason to look for something better.<br><br>Kevlar, the same material used in body armour, meets the S3 penetration standard at a fraction of the weight. Same protection. Same certification. Same site inspection. The shoe just weighs 460 grams.<br><br><i>Lighter than most trainers.</i><br><br><strong>The weight was never part of the safety requirement. It was a side effect nobody bothered fixing.</strong></p>",
        "gg9qEKQKEQ7_text": "The Safety Standard Has Nothing To Do With the Weight",
        "ggtwgd7yaBb_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section2.webp",
        "ggtwgd7yaBb_srcSet_mobile_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section2.webp"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947719287210555"
    },
    "gp_section_612947719371096635": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "79ab873492a380d786bf455a8cfd54c27ab4fb40bc29f6080cfd4a864d9bf3b2_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg5jp5xOybH_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section1.webp",
        "ggSQMRMiuol_text": "Your Boots Are Working Against You All Day Long",
        "ggezJjNqnNl_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41017.png",
        "ggezJjNqnNl_srcSet_mobile_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section1.webp",
        "ggyTRmUd0ss_text": "<p>Ask any tradesperson what hurts most by the end of a shift. Feet. Lower back. That heavy dragging feeling in the joints that never quite clears over the weekend.<br><br>That is not the job. That is what happens when you strap over a kilogram of dead weight to each foot before you have even left the house.<br><br>Traditional safety boots weigh well over 1kg per shoe. At 10,000 to 15,000 steps a day on concrete and hard ground, your legs lift that load on every single step. Your hips compensate. Your lower back absorbs what your legs cannot manage.<br><br><i><strong>\"My feet are killing me by lunchtime\" </strong></i>is not the job talking. It is the boots.</p>"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947719371096635"
    },
    "gp_section_612947719538868960": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "5ebf4d5103e4a92ceef7b2968cd9dfd9a01990a6aee08f5aef7ae80cd85c32df_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg5rfYIcy-A_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section4.webp",
        "gg5rfYIcy-A_srcSet_mobile_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section4.webp",
        "ggBfECCthge_text": "<p>There is a belief on site that weight means protection. That if a boot is light, something has been cut somewhere.<br><br>For a long time, that was fair. When steel was the only material that met S3 standards, weight was the price you paid for compliance.<br><br>But you would not pick a power drill from 1995 because it feels more solid. You choose what does the job properly.<br><br>A 460 gram shoe with a Kevlar plate and steel toecap passes the exact same S3 certification as a boot twice the weight. Same impact protection. Same puncture resistance. Same site inspection. It just does not punish your body in the process.</p>",
        "ggk9KCanWGj_text": "Heavy Boots Are Not Safer. They Are Just Older."
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947719538868960"
    },
    "gp_section_612947720209957600": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "b8f4e586887a371fddd0db09d223e123c97d15c4cb8cd86609cbfd3b85aae983_1_1_1_0__1",
        "ggNSNHojJ3l_text": "Your Boots Are Destroying Your Feet Before the Concrete Even Gets a Chance",
        "ggbH4SmoZ3v_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41021.png",
        "ggbH4SmoZ3v_srcSet_mobile_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section5.webp",
        "gghLPyCk2qj_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section5.webp",
        "gglhiZ70pao_text": "<p>Most workers blame the concrete. Hard floors. Long hours. And yes, those play a part.<br><br>But the boot itself is making it significantly worse.<br><br>Traditional safety boots are built around a rigid last and thick leather upper. The boot does not flex with your foot. It forces your foot to adapt to the shoe instead. Over an eight hour shift, that constant resistance causes friction at the heel and toe box. That is where the blisters come from. That is why your ankles feel locked up by the afternoon.<br><br>The stiffness is not a sign of quality. It is what happens when a boot is designed around a safety standard rather than a human foot.<br>A 460 gram boot that flexes like a trainer stops fighting your foot. The blisters ease. The ankle stiffness goes. The feet that were done by lunchtime start making it to the end of the shift.<br><br>The concrete is not going anywhere. But what you put on your feet before you step onto it is entirely your choice.</p>"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947720209957600"
    },
    "gp_section_612947721199813179": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "90659e740586776cb1576457757564f8f05a36df6a695dcea7d35ac29c44a2ed_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg8QfDv3jhZ_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41019.png",
        "gg8QfDv3jhZ_srcSet_mobile_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section3.webp",
        "ggAITJL6-40_text": "<p>The difference between a traditional boot and a modern lightweight one is roughly 500 grams per foot.<br><br>Run that across a full shift. At 12,000 steps a day, your legs and lower back are absorbing thousands of additional kilograms of unnecessary load. Every day. Every week you are on the tools.<br><br>Workers who made the switch describe the same thing. Still tired after a shift, but differently tired. The heavy dragging exhaustion that sits in the joints starts to ease. Back pain they had written off as permanent begins to shift.<br><br><strong>It was never the age. It was always the weight.</strong></p>",
        "ggTAX4bfxJt_text": "The Damage Adds Up Faster Than You Think",
        "ggaRtiqng48_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/section3.webp"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947721199813179"
    },
